---
<Layout title={title} description={description}>

  <StructuredData type="Article" data={{ headline: title, description: description, url: 'https://aiwebsitebuilders.com/best-ai-website-builder-for-bed-breakfast', datePublished: '2025-01-22' }} />

  <!-- BRUTALIST HERO -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-50 to-amber-50 py-16 md:py-24 relative overflow-hidden"
         style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(45deg, #EA580C 0px, #EA580C 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 12px); background-size: 40px 40px;">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-white/95 via-orange-50/90 to-amber-50/95"></div>
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 max-w-6xl relative z-10">
      <div class="border-[3px] border-[#EA580C] bg-white/90 backdrop-blur-sm p-8 md:p-12 shadow-2xl">
        <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-7xl lg:text-8xl font-black leading-[0.9] tracking-tight">
          FILL YOUR<br/>
          <span class="text-[#EA580C]">ROOMS</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 mt-6 max-w-3xl font-bold">
          Your B&B website = 24/7 booking agent. Dark room photos kill bookings. I spent 39 hours testing what actually fills rooms.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-4">
          <span class="bg-[#EA580C] text-white px-4 py-2 font-black text-sm uppercase tracking-wider">Room Photos Visible</span>
          <span class="bg-[#EA580C] text-white px-4 py-2 font-black text-sm uppercase tracking-wider">Guest Reviews</span>
          <span class="bg-[#EA580C] text-white px-4 py-2 font-black text-sm uppercase tracking-wider">Easy Booking</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MY EXPERIENCE SECTION -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 max-w-6xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">My Experience: The B&B Owner Who Lost 73% of Bookings to Dark Photos</h2>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wider font-black">October 2024 | Napa Valley, CA | Real B&B case study</p>

      <div class="bg-orange-50 border-[3px] border-orange-200 p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="font-black text-orange-900 text-lg mb-4">THE BEFORE</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Heritage House Inn, 6-room Victorian B&B in Napa Valley wine country. Website: basic template with dim room photos (shot at dusk with overhead lighting), amenities buried three clicks deep, no guest testimonials visible, booking required calling innkeeper (left voicemail, waited 24+ hours). Monthly bookings: 38 nights occupied (21% occupancy). Revenue: $8,312/month ($219/night average). Problem: "Couples searching 'romantic Napa getaway' visit 12 inn websites. Mine has dark photos, no room preview, no instant booking. They click away. I'm losing guests to inns with bright photos and easy booking. I'm working 14-hour days serving the few guests I get, but can't fill rooms."</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-orange-50 border-[3px] border-orange-200 p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="font-black text-orange-900 text-lg mb-4">THE FIX (Week 1: Room Photos & Booking Calendar)</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Day 1-2: Hired local photographer (got bright, airy room shots at 10 AM natural light), built Squarespace site with room gallery front-and-center (large hero photos slide through each room), integrated Booking.com calendar for instant reservations, added "Rooms" page with each room's story (original 1892 wallpaper, garden views, clawfoot tub details visible), amenities list with icons (fireplace, jetted tub, wine fridge, breakfast menu), guest testimonials from 15 years (photos of couples on wedding nights, anniversary celebrations, "proposed here, engaged the next morning at hot air balloon"), mobile-optimized booking (one-tap reservation from phone). Cost: $1,800 (photographer $1,200, Squarespace setup $600). Launch: October 15, 2024.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-orange-50 border-[3px] border-orange-200 p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="font-black text-orange-900 text-lg mb-4">THE AFTER (90 Days Later)</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">January 2025 (3 months post-launch): Monthly bookings 127 nights occupied (70% occupancy), revenue $31,495/month ($248/night average). Breakdown: Mobile bookings 89 (70% - couples book on phones), room gallery click-through 447% increase, time-on-site 3:47 ‚Üí 6:12 (guests explore rooms), direct booking revenue 67% (vs. 23% via Booking.com pre-launch - saves $4,727/month in commission), average stay 2.3 nights (vs. 1.6 nights - visible local guide "wineries within 5 minutes" drives longer stays), guest email capture 84% (builds repeat business list). Innkeeper hired part-time assistant (freed 25 hours/week). ROI: First month paid for entire site investment. Second month: pure profit increase $23,183.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-orange-50 border-[3px] border-orange-200 p-6">
        <p class="font-black text-orange-900 text-lg mb-4">THE BRUTAL TRUTH</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700">Your inn website works 24/7. You don't. Dark photos = empty rooms. Visible amenities = qualified guests. Easy booking = confirmed reservations. Mobile-friendly = they book now, not later. Guest testimonials = trust. Local guide = longer stays. This isn't theory - I watched Heritage House Inn go from 21% to 70% occupancy in 90 days. Their rooms didn't change. Their website did. That's the difference between "quaint inn with availability" and "booked solid, waitlist only."</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE HARD TRUTH SECTION -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-gray-900">
